## Examples

### Example 1: Adding MCP to Schedule Workflow

```json
{
  "nodes": [
    {
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.scheduleTrigger",
      "name": "Schedule Trigger"
    },
    {
      "type": "@n8n/n8n-nodes-langchain.mcpTrigger",
      "name": "MCP Server Trigger",
      "parameters": {
        "path": "workflow-name"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.set",
      "name": "Process Data"
    }
  ],
  "connections": {
    "Schedule Trigger": {
      "main": [[{"node": "Process Data"}]]
    },
    "MCP Server Trigger": {
      "main": [[{"node": "Process Data"}]]
    }
  }
}
```

### Example 2: Adding MCP to Evaluation Workflow

```json
{
  "nodes": [
    {
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.evaluationTrigger",
      "name": "Evaluation Trigger"
    },
    {
      "type": "@n8n/n8n-nodes-langchain.mcpTrigger",
      "name": "MCP Server Trigger",
      "parameters": {
        "path": "evaluation-workflow-name"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.set",
      "name": "Process Evaluation"
    }
  ],
  "connections": {
    "Evaluation Trigger": {
      "main": [[{"node": "Process Evaluation"}]]
    },
    "MCP Server Trigger": {
      "main": [[{"node": "Process Evaluation"}]]
    }
  }
}
```

## Enforcement

This pattern is MANDATORY for all n8n workflows that require programmatic access. SET is responsible for implementing MCP Server Trigger nodes, and ES is responsible for ensuring compliance with this pattern.

